n in figurative forms, show a close philological link with the Masorah of the eastern Tiberian sources and prove that the presence of figurative elements neither represents a loss nor a distortion of Masoretic knowledge, but rather illustrates a development in the Masoretic tradition.  aIssued also in print.  afunded by Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access. Unless otherwise specified individually in the content, the work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives (CC BY-NC-ND) license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aJudaism. 0aMasorah. 4aHebräische Bibel. 4aHebräische Manuskripte. 4aMikrographie. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh  aHebrew biblical manuscripts.  aMasorah.  aMicrography.2 aDeutsche Forschungsgemeinschaftefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2015 Part 1z978311076251808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z97831107009850 cEPUBz97831104253140 cprintz978311041791340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110417920zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110417920zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110417920/original  a978-3-11-070098-5 DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-076251-8 DG Plus DeG Package 2015 Part 1b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA